## Concept 2: Providers

Terraform does not know how to talk to AWS on its own. It uses plugins called **providers**. The AWS provider translates your HCL into AWS API calls. Every cloud and service has its own provider — AWS, Azure, GCP, GitHub, Cloudflare, and hundreds more. You declare which provider you need at the top of your configuration, and Terraform downloads it automatically when you initialise a project.

Think of providers as translators: Terraform speaks HCL, AWS speaks its own API, and the provider sits in the middle doing the translation.

> **Exam note:** The exam tests provider version constraints. Pay close attention to how version numbers are pinned — `~> 5.0` means "5.x but not 6.0".

### Activity 2

Create a new directory and your first config file:

```bash
mkdir terraform-lab && cd terraform-lab
touch main.tf
```

Add this to `main.tf`:

```hcl
terraform {
  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "~> 5.0"
    }
  }
}

provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-southeast-1"
}
```

> The region `ap-southeast-1` (Singapore) is correct for your stack. Your EC2, RDS, and S3 resources all live there. Do not copy `us-east-1` from random tutorials.

Then run:

```bash
terraform init
```

**Expected result:** You will see "Initialising the backend...", "Initialising provider plugins...", and finally "Terraform has been successfully initialised!" A hidden `.terraform/` directory and a `.terraform.lock.hcl` file appear. A credentials error at this stage is expected — you will fix that next.

